<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0805-B"><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;But I refuse to sink.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>They say the same thing, whether in information sessions large and small or in one-on-one appointments.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>His monthly co-payments would be $673.42, and his monthly drug premium would be $23.16.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Monthly premiums will rise 1 percent for each month you reject coverage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>&quot;The magnitude of this program change is so great we almost can't have enough help.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If so, you can always switch to a Medicare Part D plan later without paying any penalty.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line><line>You will pay a monthly premium to the company and receive a drug plan card to show your pharmacist when you fill prescriptions.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line><line>The Medicare &amp; You 2006 booklet that Medicare recently sent you lists information about drug plans and company phone numbers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="21,42,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>To be sure, this is not the last word on Medicare Part D. Some elderly consumers, buying some medications, probably will find better prices through Medicare plans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="36"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>These savings are the result of better-than-expected competition among private insurance companies, many of whom got better-than-expected deals from drug manufacturers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Social worker Irene Ilachinski sat with Maria Tarzi and looked over her list of medicines.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Warning: You can't have both a Medicare HMO and a Part D drug plan.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,25"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>So how does he -- or actually, how do my sister and I, who manage his affairs -- slash through the dozens of Medicare drug plans available in the part of suburban Washington where he lives?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="12,29,41,55"/></line><line>Would the Medigap plan pick up some of his leftover drug costs?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>Vans should start rolling into the Triangle and Charlotte areas by mid-December.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Ilachinski called up the online Medicare Prescription Drug Plan Finder and began clicking on specific brand names: Zocor, Plavix, Nexium and a half-dozen more.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>Demand on the Medicare Web site was so heavy Tuesday that its enrollment tool was unavailable for much of the day, officials at the Minnesota Linkage Line said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>&quot;I gave them my prescriptions and they pinpointed it down to two or three plans,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Many retirees may want to stay with their current prescription drug coverage through a former employer's health plan if it is comparable to what's offered through Medicare.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="49"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>However, if you reject coverage now, Medicare will charge a penalty if you change your mind later.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>In North Carolina, 16 companies are offering 38 different plans.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Just days into the launch of Medicare's biggest expansion since its inception 40 years ago -- a program that could run taxpayers $720billion in its first decade -- seniors and the people trying to advise them are incredulous about the multiplicity of options, deductibles, premiums and exceptions, which make comparisons seem overwhelming, if not impossible.</line><line>Although Part D will greatly benefit certain people, its savings are not universal.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>For one, it is possible that seniors, by gravitating toward the simplest plans, will force the system to become simpler.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>&quot;We'll be a lot more effective helping people who need a hand figuring out this new benefit -- people whose health and finances may improve significantly because of help paying for their drugs,&quot; said Janine Stiles of the Minnesota Senior Federation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>What if I can't afford the premiums?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Whichever plan you are enrolled in on Dec. 31 is the plan you will be in when the program starts on Jan. 1.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>But perhaps the worst news came last Tuesday, when Rep. Henry Waxman released a report showing that a typical senior citizen could get a better deal at Costco or Drugstore.com than in the elaborate new Medicare marketplace.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>And still, papers in hand, she grimaced.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>As it turns out -- and Ashkenaz allowed that Medicare was not particularly publicizing this wrinkle -- you can change plans every day from now until the end of the year if you want to.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>Its counselors will do that largely by helping people tap existing online resources, such as the Medicare drug plan finder that is available at www.medicare.gov.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Consider paying a slightly higher premium for a plan with fewer restrictions on your specific drugs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>But the best outreach will come from families, talking it over with their parents and aunts and uncles.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Thirty-five plans popped up.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>The coalition has been in the field for a year helping educate older and disabled beneficiaries about the Medicare drug benefit.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>They may not have family or friends to turn to for help.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>The average government subsidy per person is running at $94 monthly, rather than $109.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>So does Medicaid, the federal-state insurance program for the poor.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>How do I pick a plan that is right for me?</line><line>Medicare will reduce these costs by subsidizing the company for serving you.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>As economist Paul Krugman has argued, private markets might be the best way to produce cars and computers, but are a horrible way to deliver health care.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Premiums in Florida range from $10.95 to $104.89 a month, deductibles from $0 to $250 a year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Further, some insurers keep adjusting their offerings.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>This is the first day people on Medicare can determine their health coverage for 2006 - whether they receive care through Medicare's traditional Parts A and B or through a Medicare HMO or PPO.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="14,25,29,44,49,51"><scu uid="1" label="Open season for Medicare Part D has begun" weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>Coverage starts Jan. 1 if you have signed up by the end of this year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>What drugs are you taking?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>My Medicare Matters, which is supported by a $10 million grant from pharmaceutical company AstraZeneca, will aim to help people enrolled in Medicare get the information they need to make an informed choice about whether to sign up for Medicare Part D, as the new prescription coverage is known.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;We're doing our best to meet that need,&quot; Parks said.</line><line>During this initial enrollment, the state's 4.3 million beneficiaries have until May 15 to make a choice.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>But it's not premature to study whether it's really serving the interests of Medicare beneficiaries and the taxpayers who will pay its massive cost.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Medicare is also operating a telephone help line around the clock, 1-800-Medicare, which has an automated voice system that also allows callers to reach a real person.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>This time the results were different.</line><line>Under the least expensive plan for my father's situation, one offered by First Health Premier, he would pay an estimated $4,008.72 a year, or $3,633.84 less than he pays now.</line><line>A likely candidate was UnitedHealthcare, the company used by the AARP Medigap program.</line><line>And, depending on how big a discount a plan offers, you may be better off with one that does not cover all of them but that deeply discounts the drugs it does cover.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>In its announcement Tuesday, the council also unveiled a streamlined Web site -- www.MyMedicareMatters.org -- to help Medicare beneficiaries and their families learn about the drug benefit and plug into the enrollment process.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>A national survey of Medicare members conducted recently by the Kaiser Family Foundation and Harvard School of Public Health found that just 6 percent of respondents had even visited the Web site.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>The companies fear they may find themselves wrestling with Uncle Sam if they try to maintain what they're doing for seniors while participating in government programs at the same time.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line><line>Instead of turning the tide against a movement toward a national health care system -- which is what this administration and the drug and insurance industries are desperately trying to do -- this program will only encourage it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>In addition to presentations to senior groups across the region, HICAP's staff and 40 trained volunteers provide one-on-one counseling.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>At the moment, the average senior will pay about $32 in monthly premiums, some $5 less than predicted.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Casillas said she attended Tuesday's Elk Grove session because she is having trouble getting her questions answered.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;We're still trying to figure out what to tell them.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Drug companies that offer patient assistance programs typically have a higher income cutoff, about $19,000 a year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;It's wearing me out,&quot; Betsy Curtin confessed as she and her husband departed the James Lee Community Center near Falls Church, Va.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>First Health Premier was still the cheapest -- but $3,977.01 now, compared with $4,008.72 four days earlier.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;They may get a voicemail.&quot;</line><line>Enrollment in Medicare's new drug coverage started Tuesday, and seniors are clamoring for advice on how to navigate a crucial program that offers more than 50 options.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="11,49"><scu uid="1" label="Open season for Medicare Part D has begun" weight="3"/><scu uid="10" label="Seniors are baffled by hundreds of complex options" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Or you can research that directly at www.medicare.gov.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Questions, and concerns, were plentiful.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>It's a mess.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="12"><scu uid="10" label="Seniors are baffled by hundreds of complex options" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>How do we decide whether he should sign up for any of them and, if so, figure out the best plan for him?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>&quot;I found it to be confusing, but we really studied it,&quot; said Peterson, whose husband, Ray, 72, has drug coverage from the Department of Veterans Affairs that he plans to keep for now.</line><line>The deadline is approaching for elderly and disabled people who must decide whether and when to enroll in one of the new Medicare Part D drug plans that start Jan. 1, 2006.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="9" sums="10,11,14,23,25,41,44,51,55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>HICAP receptionist Denise King said some seniors have complained to her they are put on hold or transferred when they call Medicare, and do not get their questions answered.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Several hours later, many left a little less confused -- but not necessarily any closer to a decision.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Even if you are not on Medicaid, you might qualify for reductions on premiums, deductibles and copayments if your income falls below $14,356 ($19,246 for a couple) and you don't own a lot of liquid assets such as savings, CDs and stocks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Negrete said pharmacists are learning about the coverage to be prepared to help customers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>It's too late now to change the law, which passed Congress in 2003, and too soon to rewrite it.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>His best advice to consumers is get a good understanding of the coverage you have now, make a list of all medications now needed and decide which pharmacy you'd like to use.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Calls to the Medicare Rights Center, an independent, New York-based organization, quadrupled over previous weeks' volume.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>Worse, more than three-quarters said they have never used the Internet, although the Medicare.gov Web site provides the most efficient means of comparing the different plans.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>How do I sign up?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>The Veterans Administration, for example, doesn't operate that way.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>And the best way to sort out the competing information?</line><line>The program is too complicated, he said, too expensive and &quot;too much of a giveaway to the pharmaceutical companies.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>They were ranked in order, based on my father's total annual out-of-pocket expense for his drugs would be, including the monthly drug premium and the annual deductible for each plan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>The education campaign -- &quot;My Medicare Matters&quot; -- comes a week after people enrolled in Medicare began signing up for the new prescription benefits.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="42"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>Already, anecdotal and polling evidence shows that many seniors are baffled by the benefit, which requires beneficiaries to choose from several dozen private plans.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>They came equipped with notepads of questions and lists of medications, and with the thick red-white-and-blue handbook &quot;Medicare &amp; You.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Peter Ashkenaz, a Medicare spokesman, explained that the agency updated the plans and their prices every Monday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>The goal: to help Medicare enrollees understand the optional prescription drug coverage, which takes effect Jan. 1.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="21,57"><scu uid="39" label="Various consumer advocacy groups will assist Medicare enrollees in understanding Plan D" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Ask your ex-employer or union whether your retiree plan qualifies as &quot;creditable.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>The government's celebrated new prescription drug program for senior citizens got off to a rocky start this month, with elderly consumers fuming over its complexity and federal websites crashing under heavy traffic.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>But the plan now going into effect smacks of a political taint: The president and his party vowed to do something about drug costs for seniors but wanted at the same time to protect drug manufacturers and insurance companies no matter what.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Are you willing to switch to generics if they are an option?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Others who now are enrolled in a Medicare managed-care plan may consider signing up for an enhanced package with that insurer that will include prescription drug coverage, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Do you want to order them by mail?</line><line>It turns out that you really do need a computer to sort through drug plans because there are so many variables.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>How much do plans cost?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>That said, congressional Republicans who promised that competition among private insurance companies would improve Medicare, delivering low prices for consumers and low costs for taxpayers, now bear a heavy burden of proof.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;Well,&quot; Griffin said to Rafik, &quot;we're not going to take that one, are we?&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>His medicines cost him $636.88 a month, or $7,642.56 a year.</line><line>I called the number and got right through to a service agent in the middle of the day last Thursday, with no wait.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>What if I get drug benefits from my ex-employer's or union's retiree health plan?</line><line>The people who answer 1-800-MEDICARE can give give a list of the three cheapest plans based on your medications.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="37"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>However, few Medicare enrollees are using the online tool or any of the other information Medicare makes available at its Internet site.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Ask each company if they restrict your drugs and how.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>But Parks said many of those seeking advice are older people without computer access or skills to use Internet search tools to compare plans.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Raleigh News &amp; Observer editorial</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>If the new Medicare Part D turns out to be expensive but wonderful, it might be worth it.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="36"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>For those who do not want to use the Web site, or cannot use it, there is another option.</line><line>Last Friday, I plugged my father's drugs into the Medicare Web site.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you have no drug coverage now, it's probably wise to enroll in Part D. You can join a plan for as little as $10.95 a month.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>The United States relies on private markets to deliver health care far more than any other developed nation, and yet Americans pay far more for health care than consumers in other advanced nations.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Information on companies is also available on www.sptimes.com/medicare.</line><line>Must I get drug coverage?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Consider, among many facts in an N&amp;O report from staff writer Jean P. Fisher, that the Medicare Part D plan is going to be run by dozens of private insurance companies across the country.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Often coverage ceases when total drug costs hit $2,250, then begins again when total costs hit $5,100.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>The benefit will start Jan. 1 for those who enroll by Dec. 31.</line><line>Medicare officials have not released any information about how many people have joined a Medicare drug-insurance plan since enrollment started Nov. 15.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="42"><scu uid="1" label="Open season for Medicare Part D has begun" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Enrollment started Tuesday and continues, for those 65 and older, until May 15.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>To get Part D coverage, you must sign up with one of 19 private insurance companies offering 43 different plans in Florida.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="33,37,6"/></line><line>Some income is not counted, so if you are anywhere close to qualifying, check with Social Security toll-free at 1-800-772-1213.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>In the long term, the benefit's success will be measured in at least two ways.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>The program's arcane intricacies and implementation, preceded by a barrage of advertising, have been so criticized that some lawmakers are pushing for a two-year delay.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="20,32,40,5"><scu uid="2" label="Some lawmakers are seeking a two-year delay in Plan implementation" weight="3"/><scu uid="7" label="Plan D's intricacies have been so criticized" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;They say, `What would you do?&quot;' program coordinator Howard Houghton said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>But there are some basic steps to help consumers decide which plan, if any, is right for an individual.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>As for Martha and me, we have not yet signed my father up for a plan.</line><line>My father is 92 years old, lives in a nursing home and takes 10 prescription drugs, paid for from his savings and Social Security income.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>You've got to sign up for it.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>And if it no longer covered his drugs, would his Medigap premium decrease?</line><line>But when I looked at the Medicare Web site, the research tool there seemed easy to use.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>The program is set up to be federally subsidized but run by the commercial insurance industry, a combination that some say generates confusion.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>It's also politically smart, as anyone can tell who's paying any attention to the considerable voting clout elderly Americans have.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>You can also sign up between Jan. 1 and May 15, but the drug plan will not defray your costs until you have signed up.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>She collected information on computer printouts from senior centers and talked with state insurance advisers at a Medicare fair.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>The following editorial appeared in Tuesday's Washington Post:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>But seniors and the disabled may have to be patient.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Retiree plans offered by employers and unions are often cheaper than Part D plans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>And yet the 2003 law that created Part D specifically forbids Medicare to negotiate the same sort of bulk discounts.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;There's a lot of resources at those events and they're constantly bringing in the new information,&quot; Parks said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you want to add a Part D drug plan to traditional Medicare Parts A and B, you can contact the private drug plan directly or sign up online at www.medicare.gov or by calling toll-free 1-800-MEDICARE (633-4227).<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="14,44"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I told her that I was a reporter and that I was just testing the system; I did not ask her to go through the whole drug plan search process for me.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>&quot;My hunch is we'll know more -- maybe even get a big push in enrollments -- after families talk about the drug benefit over their Thanksgiving dinner,&quot; said Peter Ashkenaz , a spokesman for the federal Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>She sounded almost indignant about the complexity of the new Medicare Part D Prescription Drug Coverage, the federal government's effort to offer millions of older Americans a way to better afford their pills.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="35"><scu uid="7" label="Plan D's intricacies have been so criticized" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>AmeriHealth Advantage was still the most expensive, but its price had dropped to $6,978.94, from $8,454.33.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If it isn't, you probably should switch to a Medicare HMO or a Part D drug plan to avoid paying a premium penalty later on.</line><line>Part D drug plans only accompany Medicare's traditional Parts A and B, where you pick your own doctors and hospitals.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Martha says it is up to me to do all that checking if I want to, but it is not something she cares to take on.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>The so-called Part D program for the first time brings drugs under the Medicare tent that covers 42 million people.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Initially, Martha and I understood that my father was taking eight drugs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>That income figure is maddeningly low, of course, and seniors who are just a little above it, or even a good bit above it, may be in dire straits indeed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>This year it is financed largely by a $2 million grant from the drug manufacturers trade association.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>Waxman, a California Democrat, asked congressional investigators to study the 10 top-selling drugs among senior citizens, and then compare prices available at popular discounters against prices in the new Medicare Part D, which relies on private insurance companies to deliver coverage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="29,55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I called Martha and told her I wanted to give it a try.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Many &quot;patient assistance&quot; programs for low-income people will end Jan. 1.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>She encouraged Medicare beneficiaries to attend a community presentation to learn the basics.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I thought there must be some mistake.</line><line>I got a list of 42 plans.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>&quot;Anything that is going to result in [North Carolina] having additional counselors who are educated and can help people is wonderful,&quot; said Carla Obiol, the SHIIP program's director.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Only 20 of the 200 residents invited actually attended, he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;This is a bad piece of legislation, and it never should have been enacted,&quot; Rep. James P. Moran Jr., D-Va., told the community center crowd, which responded with applause.</line><line>Nearly 200 strong, they came looking for help in figuring out which among dozens of bewildering plans would buy them the most medicines for the least price.</line><line>Questions and concerns took on greater urgency after enrollment officially commenced this week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>My sister, Martha Bari, to avoid the onerous research she was fearing, considered simply choosing an insurer with a trusted name.</line><line>And then I tried again the next day with the same result.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>More than six in 10 told a Kaiser Family Foundation pollster that they understand the new drug benefit &quot;not too well&quot; or &quot;not at all.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>The annual costs of its various plans, which are being marketed by private companies, can vary by thousands of dollars, and a penalty could multiply many beneficiaries' bills by thousands more if they sign up after the deadline.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>They will help beneficiaries sort through more than 60 private plans offering drug insurance.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>It's a plan that won't help nearly as many people as it should help, and will leave some worse off than they are now.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you qualify for Medicare and already receive drugs through Medicaid or state assistance programs, you will automatically be enrolled in a Part D drug plan without having to pay premiums or large copayments.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="10,21,22,37,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>The seniors listen carefully but, invariably toward the end of the conversation, lean in close and lower their voices.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Peterson also plans to consult her longtime pharmacist before making a final selection.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Call Medicare's toll-free number, 1-800-MEDICARE, specify &quot;enrollment&quot; on the voice-mail prompt, and tell the customer service representative the drugs you take and where you live.</line><line>And the actual process of comparing drug plans was fun -- a breeze, in fact.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>The government's logic evidently is that if the companies waive drug costs, then they might be considered to be making illegal kickbacks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;I take about 20 medications, and half of them are extremely expensive, so I am really worried about this,&quot; Helen Casillas, 64, of Elk Grove told the counselors.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>If the patients then signed up for the Medicare program, the government -- and taxpayers -- would have to pay the difference.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="41"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>People can punch in the medicines they take and compare prescription plans available in their area by cost and coverage, greatly simplifying comparison shopping.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>The other (related) measure of success is how many seniors enroll.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Joan Parks, director of Sacramento's Health Insurance Counseling and Advocacy Program, or HICAP, said her office is getting more than 200 phone messages a day -- far more than the staff of eight can quickly return.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>They found that, on average, drug prices in the new Medicare were about 3 percent higher than prices available to any customer at Costco or Drugstore.com and 60 percent higher than prices in Canada.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Yet, Moran added, &quot;I want to emphasize, I don't think you have a choice.</line><line>I worked about 20 years for the Air Force,&quot; Curtin said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>The variations were astonishing, with the estimated yearly cost varying by more than 100 percent.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Beneficiaries who get traditional fee-for-service Medicare may want to consider one of the 47 stand-alone prescription drug plans offered statewide.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>Confused about the new Medicare prescription drug coverage?<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="13,18,32,49"><scu uid="10" label="Seniors are baffled by hundreds of complex options" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>The service agents are assigned to walk the caller &quot;through everything that's up there and will send them a printout -- we call it a personalized brochure,&quot; Ashkenaz said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>As of Jan. 1, Medicaid will no longer provide drugs to people who also qualify for Medicare.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Hari Peterson, 69, a retired nurse in Warwick, R.I., has survived the process.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>But that's just an estimate: The real test is whether enough healthy people stay in the program to keep insurance companies interested in offering it and to keep premiums low.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you take very many medications, be wary of picking the plan with the lowest premium.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>He now gets a discount on his drugs because he has a Medigap policy, which he buys for $93.23 a month from AARP to cover some health care costs not picked up by Medicare.</line><line>What plans are in your area?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Jack Cheevers, spokesman for the federal Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services in San Francisco, said there has been a &quot;robust&quot; use of Medicare's Web site at www.medicare.gov, which offers details of the plans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>I've been calling them for a while.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>If it turns out to be inexpensive but complicated, that also might be acceptable.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>What was going on?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Copayments can range from $0 for a 30-day generic to $75 for a brand-name drug.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Even after that, you can change plans one more time before May 15, the last time to sign up for the Medicare drug benefit with no penalty, Ashkenaz said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Expect to leave a message, but a SHINE volunteer will call you back.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Under the most expensive plan, AmeriHealth Advantage Rx Option, he would pay $8,454.33 for the same drugs from the same pharmacy -- or $811.77 more than he pays now for those drugs from that pharmacy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Michael Negrete, an official with the California Pharmacists Association, spoke at a community event Monday night to residents of a gated mobile-home park.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Today is the first day you can enroll in a Part D plan or in a Medicare HMO or PPO.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="13,29,37,43,55,57,6"><scu uid="1" label="Open season for Medicare Part D has begun" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>&quot;Doing nothing... is not the right response for America,&quot; said James L. Firman, president of the National Council on the Aging and chairman of the Access to Benefits Coalition, a collection of more than 100 groups that is coordinating the campaign.</line><line>My Medicare Matters will supplement existing education and outreach efforts in North Carolina.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I eventually learned in a phone conversation with Jim Pogue, who manages AARP insurance for the UnitedHealth Group, that my father's Medigap plan would provide discounts on any drug not covered by a Part D plan.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="3"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Some are calling more than once when they don't get a return call the same day, adding to the volume.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>How do HMOs fit in all this?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Because of the number of calls, Parks said, it may take her staff five days to return calls.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>The results: 40 possibilities, from a Humana plan with annual costs of $3,880.66 to a plan from PacifiCare that might run $10,257.12 a year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Those who decide now can still check for a better offer next week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>And the prices were lower, especially for plans at the high end.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>I'm healthy.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Are you in a nursing home that only uses one pharmacy?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>The largest single resource now operating in the state is the N.C. Seniors' Health Insurance Information Program, which has seen the number of calls to its information line, at (800) 443-9354, nearly triple in recent weeks, largely because of questions about Medicare Part D.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>He said that the insurers were starting to assess one another's plans and revise them to be more competitive.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Senior citizens who are trying to sort through their drug coverage options face many problems, a main one being that those options are complicated and difficult to compare.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>The real test, though, is whether those are lasting savings or whether the insurers will find it necessary to raise costs over time.</line><line>Over the past few days, the Medicare.gov Web site has been jammed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>And its members will have plenty of reason to get busy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you want to get your hospital and doctor care through a Medicare HMO or PPO, it will also provide your drug coverage, and usually more cheaply than traditional Medicare.</line><line>You often can save money by paying more for broader coverage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;They know very little.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>It's only fair to give this big, complicated new system a year or so to prove itself.</line><line>The theory of market competition is powerful, but it shouldn't be taken as gospel.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>If only the real world would cooperate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>And it may pay to keep checking, because some insurers are continually adjusting their offerings.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Voila!</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>How do Part D drug plans work?</line><line>Many plans require prior authorization or restrict prescription quantities for some drugs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>The Web site medicare.gov can answer many questions and help with plan comparisons.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Confusing?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>A new source of help is on the way.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>&quot;We'll do as much outreach as we can,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>It's the right thing to do for senior citizens for whom a reliable supply of affordable medicine can be a cost-effective life-saver.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>Medicare program administrator Mark McClellan urged families Tuesday to have those conversations.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>But, no, I had a printout from the first session, and there had been a change.</line><line>But the Medigap premium would remain the same whether or not he needed the supplemental drug coverage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>There is no free lunch.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line><line>Will manufacturers still offer free drugs?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>In about two weeks, the counselors will start showing up at already scheduled informational sessions about the drug benefit and will visit other sites.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>But if it turns out to be complicated and wasteful too, Americans will find it's time to go back to the drawing board on health care.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;We're just deluged,&quot; said Parks, whose program provides free, unbiased consumer advice.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>The site lets the user compare drug plans, based on the information one enters.</line><line>I set to work, blithely thinking I would could sort things out in half an hour.</line><line>First I had to find out what drugs my father was actually taking and how much he paid for them.</line><line>I went to the Web site again last Tuesday, four days after first entering my father's data.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Individuals who have less than $14,355 in annual income get free or reduced premiums.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>The new cadre of counselors also may help ease pressure on the statewide Minnesota Linkage Line, which is wrestling with a backlog of more than 1,000 calls for help enrolling in the Medicare drug program.</line><line>The council organized the national Access to Benefits Coalition last year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Then I called AARP to find out exactly what type of Medigap plan my father has and what it covers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>You probably should keep these retiree benefits as long as Medicare deems them &quot;creditable coverage.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>The thinking is that the companies might be setting aside their fees to induce patients to take drugs that were more expensive than ones offered by competitors.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;It's been driving me crazy,&quot; said Rita Reitman Sobel of Alexandria, Va., her face betraying her doubt and anxiety after Thursday's presentation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>For the first time, people on Parts A and B also add a Part D drug benefit to help pay their prescription bills.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>Only one in five said that they plan to enroll.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Plans with broader coverage charge higher premiums.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;I'm a college graduate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Signing up my father for a Medicare drug plan should be simple, especially because the Medicare.gov Web site is well designed and easy to use.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="11,23"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>It simply negotiates bulk discounts with drugmakers and pays far less than retail.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you want to join an HMO or PPO, contact them directly.</line><line>The company will charge you an annual deductible, if any, and copayments.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>The concept of covering prescription costs through Medicare is worthwhile.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Finally, after two days and many phone calls, I had the information I needed.</line><line>Only after checking with the nursing home did she get the complete list of 10.</line><line>Medicare says it has 7,500 such service representatives handling calls 24 hours a day, seven days a week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>It's hopelessly confusing.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>What are the pitfalls?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>It took only 10 minutes to get the list of the drug plans and their prices for my father from the Medicare Web site.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>For that, you get coverage if you suddenly become sick and you avoid premium penalties later in life, when you are taking drugs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Without the AARP Medigap discount, his drugs would cost nearly 40 percent more: $1,044.72 a month, or $12,536.64 a year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>But as seniors start signing up -- and they have until May 15, when a late fee kicks in -- it's important not to judge the plan by the inevitable initial glitches and anticipatory fears.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>&quot;This new initiative with counselors and computers will help.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>Given the enormous sums that Congress poured into the Medicare subsidy, that's bizarre.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Parks said HICAP isn't taking on new volunteers at this time because she doesn't have the staff or time needed to train them on the complicated new coverage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>Six counselors toting laptop computers will begin scouring the Twin Cities in a van in search of Medicare beneficiaries who need help signing up for the new drug benefit, officials said Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="23,29,51"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>That meant that unless a Medicare plan was cheaper than the $7,642.56 a year my father pays for his drugs with the AARP discount, he might as well not sign up for a new plan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Why?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;People know the marketing materials arrived in the mail... that there's a benefit, but whether it's right for them is a complete mystery to them,&quot; spokeswoman Deane Beebe said Friday afternoon.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Later, the retired Realtor said, &quot;I am terrified by it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I asked Ashkenaz: What happens if you choose a plan and then the next week it becomes cheaper, or another plan becomes cheaper?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>If you rely on one of them, contact the manufacturer for details.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>Medicare officials are encouraging people to call the (800)MEDICARE telephone assistance line or go online to get enrollment information.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Who knows -- maybe the prices will rise in the next month, and we would want to be signed up before that happens.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>In northern Virginia, the Fairfax Area Agency on Aging has trained volunteers to assist local residents who walk through the door, sometimes carrying a shoebox of pill bottles.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>Counselors will work with the Minnesota Access to Benefits Coalition, which Stiles coordinates.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>And how would my father's Medigap policy be affected if he signed up for the Medicare drug plan?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Oh, it's not as bad as it will be for a lot of seniors.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;I don't know if there's a plan that takes all of them,&quot; she said, &quot;but we'll see what's available at least.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>When does Part D drug coverage begin?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,16"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>Former Louisiana Sen. John Breaux, D, one of the benefit's congressional authors and now chairman of the Medicare Rx Education Network, reckons that the benefit will be a success if half of eligible seniors enroll.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>And you will be paying the rate that was quoted when you enrolled.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Around computers in an Alexandria apartment complex's community center, several seniors paired Friday with workers from the city's Office of Aging and Adult Services and tried to make sense of the future.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>His monthly co-payments would be $142.70, lower than with any other plan, and his monthly premium would be $22.91, among the lowest of all the plans.</line><line>And she wonders how many people will.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>The company negotiates discounts from drug manufacturers and resells to you, usually at a below-market price.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Through Dec. 31, consumers can change their minds.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>Another, it now turns out, is that many drug companies that have been giving drugs (or selling them at low cost) to seniors in order to promote their products while giving elderly people a break aren't going to offer such programs anymore.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>No. Just like Part B doctor coverage, the new Part D drug coverage is optional.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="12,32,43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>&quot;It's challenging.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>She said people should call once and &quot;know we will call them back.&quot;</line><line>Medicare's new drug coverage, called Part D, goes into effect Jan. 1.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="22"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I discovered, instead, that it took two days to get the information I needed before even starting to use the Medicare Web site.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>And she has a computer and some savvy using it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Companies are clamoring to compete, and some are adding to the confusion by offering dozens of plans with a welter of wrinkles and widely varying prices.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>There were six additional plans that were not there before, for a total of 48 instead of 42.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Your costs will vary widely from plan to plan.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Actual coverage begins Jan.1.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>One of my drugs alone is $200, and others are nearly that high.&quot;</line><line>While some feel rushed to make a choice, others may wait until the last minute.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I told her that I now think the best strategy is to sign up for the cheapest plan and then keep checking back every week on the Medicare site to see if a better option comes along.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>A national coalition of senior and consumer advocacy groups said Tuesday it will dispatch a fleet of vans equipped with wireless computers and trained staff to North Carolina and 26 other states.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>In terms of your out-of-pocket expenses, such a plan might work better than a plan that covers every drug but offers smaller discounts.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>A few feet away, MaryAnn Griffin typed in the same details and appropriate dosages for Tarzi's cousin, Mahboub Rafik, and then hit enter.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>The local effort is part of a national campaign and funded by a $10 million grant from British drugmaker AstraZeneca to the National Council on the Aging.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>But the most amazing thing was what happened next.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>The challenge is for beneficiaries to figure out which of the 47 stand-alone drug plans or seven Medicare managed-care health plans available in Sacramento is right for them.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>I had the ability to compare any three plans side by side, in as many combinations as I chose.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>A HICAP-sponsored information session Tuesday at the Elk Grove Senior Center drew an audience of 85.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line><line>There's a wait for one-on-one HICAP counseling appointments.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>When the counselors explain that they can't cross that line, their clients try a different approach: &quot;`What would you tell your mother to do?&quot;'</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Do you care which pharmacy supplies your drugs?</line><line>I specified their doses and the preferred pharmacy, which is 35 miles from his nursing home but the only one the nursing home will use.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0004"><line>The new computer site, financed in part by the federal government, supplements the Medicare Web site that some older people have complained is cumbersome and at times is slow because of heavy Internet traffic.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0294"><line>Consumers who want coverage to start in January can make a selection by Dec. 31, but they can also wait until May 15 to select a plan, without penalty.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>The first is by cost: to seniors and to the government.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Next came a call to the pharmacy to find out what the drugs would cost without my father's AARP discount, which involved providing a list of the medications and then waiting for a call with the prices.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,43,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Florida's SHINE program can give one-on-one advice if you call toll-free 1-800-963-5337.</line><line>If you sign up for both, Medicare will disenroll you from the HMO and put you on traditional Medicare Parts A and B. Some companies, like Humana, Blue Cross-Blue Shield and WellCare offer both HMOs and Part D plans so be careful what you sign up for.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>Tuesday, it could grind to a halt.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>The next edition of Congress, which unfortunately won't be in until after the 2006 elections, will have a repair job on its hands.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051126.0135"><line>And it's worth remembering that congressional skeptics were wrong before: A year ago they predicted that insurance companies would balk at entering the Medicare market, but today there are dozens with Medicare drug offerings.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Those considerations can affect the price you will be charged.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0033"><line>Make sure the company includes your drugs on its formulary and will let you use the pharmacy of your choice.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>All of that bodes ill for a benefit that its creators have promoted as the wave of the future: the first example of 21st-century, public-private health cooperation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051115.0354"><line>&quot;The worst part is that the people in charge are just learning it,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>Via the Internet -- and searches that most seniors say are beyond their ken.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051115.0016"><line>That's because it's the first day of open enrollment for Medicare Part D, the Medicare drug benefit for seniors.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="13,19,21,22,36,40,42,43,48"><scu uid="1" label="Open season for Medicare Part D has begun" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051119.0012"><line>What she and the rest of the audience heard was hardly reassuring.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0177"><line>The Bush administration is about as likely to admit the Republican Medicare drug assistance plan that was rushed through Congress has flaws as it is to say, &quot;Uh, you know there were some questions about the intelligence on Iraq.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051122.0321"><line>Many older adults have complained that the program is overly complex, and some advocates fear that people who would be helped by the benefit will throw their hands up and fail to sign up.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="10" label="Seniors are baffled by hundreds of complex options" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051123.0247"><line>Where do you live?</line></document></collection>